Preheat your oven to 180°C. Remove the root and dark green top from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice widthways. Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed, no need to peel), then halve lengthways and thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Thinly slice the @closed cup mushrooms{150%g}. Drain and rinse the @borlotti beans{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

In a large #frying pan{}, heat a glug of @olive oil{} over a medium-high heat. Fry the carrot, leek, @rosemary{1%sprig} and @bay leaf{1} until the carrot is soft and beginning to colour, stirring occasionally, ~{6-8%minutes}. Don't forget to remove the rosemary and bay leaf before serving!

In the meantime, place the @portobello mushrooms{3} on a lined #baking tray{}. In a #small bowl{} mix half the grated garlic with @olive oil{1%tbsp per person} and add a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Drizzle the oil over the mushrooms. Roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20%minutes}, then remove and set aside.

Add the @Provencal herbs{½%tsp}, sliced closed cup mushrooms and remaining garlic to the frying pan, stir. Cook for ~{3%minutes}, then add the beans, @red wine stock paste{28%g} and @water{500%ml}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot, bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened slightly, ~{10-15%minutes}. Meanwhile, add a drizzle of @olive oil{} and a sprinkling of @salt{} to the top of the @ciabatta{1}, wrap in #foil{} and warm on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{15%minutes}.

== Pesto ==

Heat a small frying pan over medium-low heat and toast the @hazelnuts{25} until lightly coloured. Remove from the pan and roughly chop. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(chopped, stalks and all). Pick the @tarragon{1}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped, stalks discarded) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop. In another small bowl, mix together the hazelnuts, half the chopped parsley and the @olive oil{3%tbsp}. Season to taste with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside.

== To Serve ==

Mash up some of the beans with the back of a #fork{} to help thicken the stew. Stir in the @baby spinach{125%g}, tarragon and remaining parsley. Cover with a lid and continue cooking until the spinach has wilted, ~{3-5%minutes}. Drain any excess liquid from the portobello mushrooms and thickly slice. Thickly slice the ciabatta. Serve the stew in #bowls{}, topped with the sliced mushrooms and parsley pesto, with the ciabatta slices on the side. Enjoy!

> Chef Lizzie's hearty and wholesome vegetarian stew is perfect for wintery nights.

> Mashed up and combined with fresh veg and lots of lovely herbs, borlotti beans bulk up and thicken stews as a great source of dietary fibre.